ork_root_id\\\" content=\\\"20248084\\\" /><meta name=\\\"octolytics-dimension-repository_network_root_nwo\\\" content=\\\"apache/ant\\\" />\\n  \\n\\n\\n\\n    \\n\\n    <meta name=\\\"turbo-body-classes\\\" content=\\\"logged-out env-production page-responsive\\\">\\n  <meta name=\\\"disable-turbo\\\" content=\\\"false\\\">\\n\\n\\n  <meta name=\\\"browser-stats-url\\\" content=\\\"https://api.github.com/_private/browser/stats\\\">\\n\\n  <meta name=\\\"browser-errors-url\\\" content=\\\"https://api.github.com/_private/browser/errors\\\">\\n\\n  <meta name=\\\"release\\\" content=\\\"2116e0f039a7964a5d5a1f5c51a65dfc094e55c7\\\">\\n  <meta name=\\\"ui-target\\\" content=\\\"full\\\">\\n\\n  <link rel=\\\"mask-icon\\\" href=\\\"https://github.githubassets.com/assets/pinned-octocat-093da3e6fa40.svg\\\" color=\\\"#000000\\\">\\n  <link rel=\\\"alternate icon\\\" class=\\\"js-site-favicon\\\" type=\\\"image/png\\\" href=\\\"https://github.githubassets.com/favicons/favicon.png\\\">\\n  <link rel=\\\"icon\\\" class=\\\"js-site-favicon\\\" type=\\\"image/svg+xml\\\" href=\\\"https://github.githubassets.com/favicons/favicon.svg\\\" data-base-href=\\\"https://github.githubassets.com/favicons/favicon\\\">\\n\\n<meta name=\\\"theme-color\\\" content=\\\"#1e2327\\\">\\n<meta name=\\\"color-scheme\\\" content=\\\"light dark\\\" />\\n\\n\\n\\n[1190 more lines in file. Use offset=261 to continue.]\"}], \"isError\": false, \"timestamp\": 1777785625625}]}\n/home/vjovanov/c/forge/forge4/graalvm-reachability-metadata/forge/logs/org.apache.ant:ant-launcher:1.8.1/add-new-library-support/pi-generation-2026-05-03T05-21-50-190738Z.log:8918:[thinking] **Evaluating coverage instrumentation**\n/home/vjovanov/c/forge/forge4/graalvm-reachability-metadata/forge/logs/org.apache.ant:ant-launcher:1.8.1/add-new-library-support/pi-generation-2026-05-03T05-21-50-190738Z.log:8920:[thinking] I’m trying to figure out coverage instrumentation. It seems that the appended jar shouldn’t be the original if it’s not instrumented. Also, a custom classloader might define a Locator with a null parent, but it shouldn't be bootstrap. There’s definitely some confusion around this, and I’ve got to clarify what’s happening with the jars and classloader. This feels a bit complex, but I'm working through it!\n/home/vjovanov/c/forge/forge4/graalvm-reachability-metadata/forge/logs/org.apache.ant:ant-launcher:1.8.1/add-new-library-support/pi-generation-2026-05-03T05-21-50-190738Z.log:8924:[thinking] I need to create a dedicated LocatorTest that will include tests for class$ and resource getResource. It seems I should keep a public top-level structure for the tests. I'm considering whether to remove the existing Ant_launcherTest placeholder or just leave it as is. The rules suggest a one-to-one mapping, but I need to decide if I can edit the placeholder or repurpose it for general APIs, given the coverage requirements. Should I make the test classes public to adhere to rules?\n/home/vjovanov/c/forge/forge4/graalvm-reachability-metadata/forge/logs/org.apache.ant:ant-launcher:1.8.1/add-new-library-support/pi-generation-2026-05-03T05-21-50-190738Z.log:8934:[thinking] I'm thinking about testing the URI APIs, but it seems I can focus on the active class instead of dynamic ones. Having just one test might suffice, as long as it provides high coverage. I could test `getClassSource(Locator.class)` to see if it returns correctly in native scenarios, but it appears that resources might not be available. Maybe I could just use a non-existing resource to see how it behaves? That could make for an interesting test!\n/home/vjovanov/c/forge/forge4/graalvm-reachability-metadata/forge/logs/org.apache.ant:ant-launcher:1.8.1/add-new-library-support/pi-generation-2026-05-03T05-21-50-190738Z.log:8940:[recv] {\"type\": \"message_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Evaluating coverage instrumentation**\\n\\nI’m trying to figure out coverage instrumentation. It seems that the appended jar shouldn’t be the original if it’s not instrumented. Also, a custom classloader might define a Locator with a null parent, but it shouldn't be bootstrap. There’s definitely some confusion around this, and I’ve got to clarify what’s happening with the jars and classloader. This feels a bit complex, but I'm working through it!\\n\\n**Evaluating test structure**\\n\\nI need to create a dedicated LocatorTest that will include tests for class$ and resource getResource. It seems I should keep a public top-level structure for the tests. I'm considering whether to remove the existing Ant_launcherTest placeholder or just leave it as is. The rules suggest a one-to-one mapping, but I need to decide if I can edit the placeholder or repurpose it for general APIs, given the coverage requirements. Should I make the test classes public to adhere to rules?\\n\\n**Revising test class structure**\\n\\nI see the need to ensure the active class is public, which the existing top-level violates, so I should fix that. I could place tests in the existing file, but the name Ant_launcherTest doesn’t match the active class, making it confusing. Creating a LocatorTest.java makes sense to avoid scaffold-only issues. I plan to use assertj for assertions and ensure that my JUnit methods are package-private. \\n\\nThe first test will check if a null loader falls back correctly, while another will verify that a resource from the Launcher class returns the expected results.\\n\\n**Considering URI API tests**\\n\\nI'm thinking about testing the URI APIs, but it seems I can focus on the active class instead of dynamic ones. Having just one test might suffice, as long as it provides high coverage. I could test `getClassSource(Locator.class)` to see if it returns correctly in native scenarios, but it appears that resources might not be available. Maybe I could just use a non-existing resource to see how it behaves? That could make for an interesting test!\"