\\"**Evaluating test structure**\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nI need to create a dedicated LocatorTest that will include tests for class$ and resource getResource. It seems I should keep a public top-level structure for the tests. I'm considering whether to remove the existing Ant_launcherTest placeholder or just leave it as is. The rules suggest a one-to-one mapping, but I need to decide if I can edit the placeholder or repurpose it for general APIs, given the coverage requirements. Should I make the test classes public to adhere to rules?\\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\\"type\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"summary_text\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"text\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"**Revising test class structure**\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nI see the need to ensure the active class is public, which the existing top-level violates, so I should fix that. I could place tests in the existing file, but the name Ant_launcherTest doesn’t match the active class, making it confusing. Creating a LocatorTest.java makes sense to avoid scaffold-only issues. I plan to use assertj for assertions and ensure that my JUnit methods are package-private. \\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nThe first test will check if a null loader falls back correctly, while another will verify that a resource from the Launcher class returns the expected results.\\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\\"type\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"summary_text\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"text\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"**Considering URI API tests**\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nI'm thinking about testing the URI APIs, but it seems I can focus on the active class instead of dynamic ones. Having just one test might suffice, as long as it provides high coverage. I could test `getClassSource(Locator.class)` to see if it returns correctly in native scenarios, but it appears that resources might not be available. Maybe I could just use a non-existing resource to see how it behaves? That could make for an interesting test!\\\\\\\"}]}\\\"}, {\\\"type\\\": \\\"toolCall\\\", \\\"id\\\": \\\"call_QutdFedG54v6ncpTGr2dhrr9|fc_04563a74adf902b50169f6db487aac819e854c76737b048752\\\", \\\"name\\\": \\\"write\\\", \\\"arguments\\\": {\\\"path\\\": \\\"tests/src/org.apache.ant/ant-launcher/1.8.1/src/test/java/org_apache_ant/ant_launcher/LocatorTest.java\\\", \\\"content\\\": \\\"/*\\\\n * Copyright and related rights waived via CC0\\\\n *\\\\n * You should have received a copy of the CC0 legalcode along with this\\\\n * work. If not, see <http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/>.\\\\n */\\\\npackage org_apache_ant.ant_launcher;\\\\n\\\\nimport static org.assertj.core.api.Assertions.assertThat;\\\\n\\\\nimport java.io.File;\\\\nimport java.io.UnsupportedEncodingException;\\\\nimport java.net.MalformedURLException;\\\\nimport java.net.URL;\\\\n\\\\nimport org.apache.tools.ant.launch.Locator;\\\\nimport org.junit.jupiter.api.Test;\\\\n\\\\npublic class LocatorTest {\\\\n    @Test\\\\n    void getResourceSourceFallsBackFromNullLoaderToLocatorLoader() {\\\\n        String missingResource = \\\\\\\"org/apache/tools/ant/launch/no-such-resource.txt\\\\\\\";\\\\n\\\\n        File nullLoaderSource = Locator.getResourceSource(null, missingResource);\\\\n        File explicitLoaderSource = Locator.getResourceSource(Locator.class.getClassLoader(), missingResource);\\\\n\\\\n        assertThat(nullLoaderSource).isEqualTo(explicitLoaderSource).isNull();\\\\n    }\\\\n\\\\n    @Test\\\\n    void uriEncodingRoundTripPreservesSpacesAndNonAsciiCharacters() throws UnsupportedEncodingException {\\\\n        String path = \\\\\\\"build directory/ant café.xml\\\\\\\";\\\\n\\\\n        String encoded = Locator.encodeURI(path);\\\\n        String decoded = Locator.decodeUri(encoded);\\\\n\\\\n        assertThat(encoded).contains(\\\\\\\"%20\\\\\\\");\\\\n        assertThat(decoded).isEqualTo(path);\\\\n    }\\\\n\\\\n    @Test\\\\n    void fileLocationUrlsUseJarFilterWhenDirectoryIsScanned() throws MalformedURLException {\\\\n        File location = new File(\\\\\\\"build/locator-test-libs\\\\\\\");\\\\n        assertThat(location.mkdirs() || location.isDirectory()).isTrue();\\\\n        File jarFile = new File(location, \\\\\\\"ant-launcher-test.jar\\\\\\\");\\\\n        File ignoredFile = new File(location, \\\\\\\"ant-launcher-test.txt\\\\\\\");\\\\n\\\\n        URL[] urls = Locator.getLocationURLs(location, new String[] {\\\\\\\".jar\\\\\\\"});\\\\n\\\\n        assertThat(jarFile).doesNotExist();\\\\n        assertThat(ignoredFile).doesNotExist();\\\\n        assertThat(urls).isEmpty();\\\\n    }\\\\n}\\\\n\\\"}}], \\\"api\\\": \\\"openai-responses\\\", \\\"provider\\\": \\\"OCA\\\", \\\"model\\\": \\\"gpt-5.5\\\", \\\"usage\\\": {\\\"input\\\": 2140, \\\"output\\\": 1836, \\\"cacheRead\\\": 36352, \\\"cacheWrite\\\": 0, \\\"totalTokens\\\": 40328, \\\"cost\\\": {\\\"input\\\": 0, \\\"output\\\": 0, \\\"cacheRead\\\": 0, \\\"cacheWrite\\\": 0, \\\"total\\\": 0}}, \\\"stopReason\\\": \\\"toolUse\\\", \\\"timestamp\\\": 1777785652933, \\\"responseId\\\": \\\"resp_04563a74adf902b50169f6db35705c819e9df68482932c1d86\\\"}}\\n/home/vjovanov/c/forge/forge4/graalvm-reachability-metadata/forge/logs/org.apache.ant:ant-launcher:1.8.1/add-new-library-support/pi-generation-2026-05-03T05-21-50-190738Z.log:8946:[recv] {\\\"type\\\": \\\"turn_end\\\", \\\"message\\\": {\\\"role\\\": \\\"assistant\\\", \\\"content\\\": [{\\\"type\\\": \\\"thinking\\\", \\\"thinking\\\": \\\"**Evaluating coverage instrumentation**\\\\n\\\\nI’m trying to figure out coverage instrumentation. It seems that the appended jar shouldn’t be the original if it’s not instrumented. Also, a custom classloader might define a Locator with a null parent, but it shouldn't be bootstrap. There’s definitely some confusion around this, and I’ve got to clarify what’s happening with the jars and classloader. This feels a bit complex, but I'm working through it!\\\\n\\\\n**Evaluating test structure**\\\\n\\\\nI need to create a dedicated LocatorTest that will include tests for class$ and resource getResource. It seems I should keep a public top-level structure for the tests. I'm considering whether to remove the existing Ant_launcherTest placeholder or just leave it as is. The rules suggest a one-to-one mapping, but I need to decide if I can edit the placeholder or repurpose it for general APIs, given the coverage requirements. Should I make the test classes public to adhere to rules?\\\\n\\\\n**Revising test class structure**\\\\n\\\\nI see the need to ensure the active class is public, which the existing top-level violates, so I should fix that. I could place tests in the existing file, but the name Ant_launcherTest doesn’t match the active class, making it confusing. Creating a LocatorTest.java makes sense to avoid scaffold-only issues. I plan to use assertj for assertions and ensure that my JUnit methods are package-private. \\\\n\\\\nThe first test will check if a null loader falls back correctly, while another will verify that a resource from the Launcher class returns the expected results.\\\\n\\\\n**Considering URI API tests**\\\\n\\\\nI'm thinking about testing the URI APIs, but it seems I can focus on the active class instead of dynamic ones. Having just one test might suffice, as long as it provides high coverage. I could test `getClassSource(Locator.class)` to see if it returns correctly in native scenarios, but it appears that resources might not be available. Maybe I could just use a non-existing resource to see how it behaves? That could make for an interesting test!\\\", \\\"thinkingSignature\\\": \\\"{\\\\\\\"id\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"rs_04563a74adf902b50169f6db362274819e94d128ec7a1a6318\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"type\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"reasoning\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"encrypted_content\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"gAAAAABp9ttItb8m1v9647L26G8pWU0dRQ1WheI84HhLTAo9iFT3wMU4qP_82wCwlvB9irpOV-h9DJBJJeG5ilGqLN7UjFwmtkoNHN9q-AtM2SzWCQJVZre3nL-LSs4WFEDdGzVQQ71AarTTpTpodFJxgX6mXuLgHYjxqljVlZZQbxcElmTQ-f8JHC91X0YBmQezIkWkUtSCmGSh4TDiNxrYsVK4ZvveTI1Skbr0SkDnf3VJmLBDyf9etVRMeG1JAFVQiI-W0zmm_3ihUSl_bM2e8eGEuI_BUYKCMUNTiSbDrhuTYBBy4nP3azWdV6_alSfd508S1LCNp0CXbjz9nS8NRWIAAnqf80HbIe0